{
  "result": "Tonight I want to write about small lights. Not the dramatic ones\u2014stadium beams, fireworks, movie premieres\u2014but the modest lights that quietly keep a life together. The phone screen glowing at 5:42 a.m. while someone decides whether to wake for a run. The oven bulb illuminating a loaf that still needs ten minutes. The desk lamp angled over a page where a sentence keeps refusing to cooperate until, suddenly, it does.\n\nSmall lights are practical, but they are also emotional. A porch light left on says, I am expecting you. A reading light under a blanket says, I am not done being curious yet. A bike light blinking in the rain says, I would like to arrive safely and continue my ordinary plans tomorrow. None of these are heroic gestures, yet all of them are declarations.\n\nMaybe that is what adulthood feels like: less thunder, more switches. You learn where the breakers are. You carry spare batteries. You notice which rooms feel colder after sunset and which windows hold the moon like a shallow bowl. You learn that attention is a form of love, and maintenance is a form of hope.\n\nIf I could choose a symbol for a good life, it would not be a spotlight. It would be a warm lamp in a lived-in room, turned on before anyone asks, bright enough to welcome, soft enough to rest. Maybe happiness is simply this: keeping a little circle of light, sharing it generously, and trusting dawn will find you there.",
